"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92201","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-14","<p>The Government has confirmed that interconnection will be eligible to participate in the Capacity Market auction from 2015 onwards.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-14T11:45:32.9287262Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92201/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92201/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-09-26","Electricity Interconnectors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, under what timetable electrical interconnectors will be allowed to participate in the capacity market auctions on an equal basis with domestic generators.","false","Biography information for Dan Byles","North Warwickshire","Dan Byles","209674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92202","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-14","<p>The Government made clear in December 2011 when it announced its decision to develop a Capacity Market that interconnected capacity should in principle be able to participate within the mechanism. We have worked since that time to achieve this aim, including discussing this issue with the European Commission on a number of occasions.</p><p>On 25<sup>th</sup> September, we published, for consultation, our proposals for enabling interconnectors to participate in the Capacity Market. As part of this process, we will continue to discuss this issue with the Commission before introducing legislation in early 2015.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-14T11:44:53.3998469Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92202/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92202/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-09-26","Electricity Interconnectors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what discussions officials in his Department have had with the European Commission on the principle of electrical interconnectors being allowed to bid in the new capacity market auctions.","false","Biography information for Dan Byles","North Warwickshire","Dan Byles","209675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92203","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-16","<p>DECC uses the following three performance ratings:</p><ul><li>Exceptional performance</li><li>Effective performance</li><li>Need for improvement/ developing</li></ul><p>Table 1 summarises the performance ratings for 2013-14.</p><p>Table 1</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Exceptional performance</em></p></td><td><p>359</p></td><td><p>25.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Effective performance</em></p></td><td><p>977</p></td><td><p>68.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Need for improving/developing</em></p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>6.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>1428</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>All staff with an Exceptional Performance rating were eligible for a performance related payment, as shown in Table 2.</p><p>Table 2</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Eligible for performance related payment</em></p></td><td><p>359</p></td><td><p>25.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Not eligible for performance related payment</em></p></td><td><p>1069</p></td><td><p>74.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>1428</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-10-16T14:35:31.7895618Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92203/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92203/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many officials in his Department completed the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System in 2013-14; how many and what proportion of those officials received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark; and how many and what proportion (i) did and (ii) did not qualify for a bonus under that process.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92204","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-16","<p>DECC uses the following three performance ratings:</p><ul><li>Exceptional performance</li><li>Effective performance</li><li>Need for improvement/ developing</li></ul><p>Table 1 summarises 2013/14 performance ratings for staff who declared that they had a disability. Figures are for staff headcount.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Exceptional performance</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Effective performance</p></td><td><p>58</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Need for improvement/developing</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>82</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Table 2 below provides additional data in relation to the performance ratings of staff who declared that they didn’t have a disability, and for those who didn’t declare their disability status.</p><p>Table 2</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><em>Exceptional performance</em></p></td><td><p><em>Effective performance</em></p></td><td><p><em>Need for improvement/developing</em></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Declared that they had a disability</em></p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>58</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>82</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Declared that they didn’t have a disability</em></p></td><td><p>273</p></td><td><p>680</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>1008</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Disability status not declared</em></p></td><td><p>76</p></td><td><p>239</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>338</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>359</p></td><td><p>977</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>1428</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Table 3 below summarises 2013/14 performance ratings for full- and part-time staff. Figures are for staff headcount.</p><p>Table 3</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><em>Exceptional performance</em></p></td><td><p><em>Effective performance</em></p></td><td><p><em>Need for improvement/developing</em></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Full-time</em></p></td><td><p>333</p></td><td><p>898</p></td><td><p>87</p></td><td><p>1318</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Part-time</em></p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>79</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>110</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>359</p></td><td><p>977</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>1428</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-10-16T14:34:26.5395565Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92204/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92204/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many officials in his Department who received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark under the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System (i) had a disability, (ii) worked full-time and (iii) worked part-time in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92205","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-15","<p>Core Defra Performance markings split by gender, ethnicity, age, disability and working pattern for grades AA – Grade 6 for 2013-14 are still being analysed internally and have not yet been published. This data will form part of the annual Workforce Monitoring Report, which will be published on <a href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.defra.gov.uk</a> by 31 January 2015.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","209481","2014-10-15T14:26:22.6250457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92205/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92205/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many officials in her Department who received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark under the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System (i) had a disability, (ii) worked full-time and (iii) worked part-time in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92206","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-15","<p>1865 members of staff at grades AA-G6 in Core Defra completed the Performance Management System in 2013/14.</p><p> </p><p>The breakdown of markings is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Excellent - 434 (23%)</p><p> </p><p>Good -1305 (70%)</p><p> </p><p>Must Improve - 126 (7%)</p><p> </p><p>Performance bonuses will be paid to all staff who received an ‘excellent’ marking.</p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-15T14:25:10.2994003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92206/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92206/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many officials in her Department completed the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System in 2013-14; how many and what proportion of those officials received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark; and how many and what proportion (i) did and (ii) did not qualify for a bonus under that process.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92207","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-15","<p>Core Defra Performance markings split by gender, ethnicity, age, disability and working pattern for grades AA – Grade 6 for 2013-14 are still being analysed internally and have not yet been published. This data will form part of the annual Workforce Monitoring Report, which will be published on <a href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.defra.gov.uk</a> by 31 January 2015.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","209628","2014-10-15T14:26:22.5156349Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92207/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92207/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many officials in her Department of each (a) gender, (b) ethnicity and (c) age received the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System's (i) exceeded, (ii) met and (iii) must improve performance mark in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92208","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-15","<p>The study to determine whether cage-based breeding can meet the needs of game birds (AW1303) has not been published because it is still being peer reviewed.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-15T14:29:07.7257592Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92208/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92208/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-26","Game: Birds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 1 September 2014 to Question 206013, what the reasons are for the delay in publication of the study commissioned by her Department.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","209555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92209","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-16","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office recently funded a project led by the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds (RSPB) to carry out the first ever stocktake of species in the UK’s Overseas Territories (UKOTs). The study, completed between January 2013 and March 2014, brought together all known species records and conservation assessments. It found that there are at least 1,500 endemic species in the UKOTs and that 145 (9%) of these have had their global conservation status assessed.</p><p> </p><p>The report of the study’s findings, ‘The UK’s Wildlife Overseas: A stocktake of nature in our Overseas Territories’, was published on 5 June 2014 and can be found on the RSPB’s website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.rspb.org.uk/whatwedo/projects/details.aspx?id=369443" target="_blank">www.rspb.org.uk/whatwedo/projects/details.aspx?id=369443</a></p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-16T14:26:17.7873444Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92209/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92209/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-26","Nature Conservation: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many of the species in the UK's Overseas Territories have had their conservation status assessed.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","209783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92210","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-15","<p>In the UK we work across Government to deliver co-ordinated support to the Territories on natural environment issues. Each Department leads on its respective areas of responsibility. Under the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s White Paper, ‘The Overseas Territories: Security, Success and Sustainability’, Defra leads on biodiversity and climate change adaptation and is committed to providing support for endangered species and habitats. This includes work through the ‘Darwin Plus: Overseas Territories Environment and Climate Fund’ launched in October 2012 and implementation of the UK Overseas Territories Biodiversity Strategy. Together with its Agencies, Defra has continued to provide technical and policy advice and ensured the delivery of key research in the Territories.</p><p> </p><p>We recently published a comprehensive update on ongoing and planned UK Government activities in support of the UK Overseas Territories Biodiversity Strategy, which sets out in detail some of our activities in these areas:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-overseas-territories-biodiversity-strategy-update" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-overseas-territories-biodiversity-strategy-update</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Actions range from co-funding an officer based in the Falkland Islands, responsible for implementing the Agreement on the Conservation of Albatrosses and Petrels on behalf of the South Atlantic Overseas Territories, to funding environmental mainstreaming in Anguilla to help put environmental considerations at the heart of decision making.</p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-15T16:07:28.6837948Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92210/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92210/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-26","Nature Conservation: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office publication, Overseas Territories, Security, Success and Sustainability, published in November 2012, what progress her Department has made on each of the environmental Priorities for Action in that paper; and what further steps she plans to take to deliver those priorities.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","209787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92211","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-15","<p>The Government is committed to managing the marine environment for the benefit of all users, including both recreational and commercial fishermen. We have no plans to designate sea bass as a species which can only be fished during recreational angling.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-15T14:29:47.6371692Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92211/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92211/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-26","White Fish: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will designate sea bass as a species which can only be fished during recreational angling.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","Mr John Spellar","209741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92212","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-16","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) is due to complete a review into its monitoring and reporting of breaches of welfare legislation by the end of October.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Previously, only major and critical breaches were recorded, along with the actions taken to correct these. The FSA review is now also looking to strengthen recording of minor breaches. These minor breaches include where back-up stunning equipment is used or a second stun is carried out without the intervention of the Official Veterinarian and where there has been no injury, avoidable pain, distress or suffering to an animal. As with major and critical breaches, information on minor breaches would be collated centrally and reported to Defra, Welsh and Scottish Government on a monthly basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-16T16:55:41.4732601Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92212/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92212/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-26","Slaughterhouses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 3 September 2014 to Question 193828, what steps she has taken to ensure the accuracy of data collected by the Food Standards Agency on mis-stunning of animals for slaughter.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","209694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92213","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>On 16 September the Ukraine Parliament (Rada) ratified the EU-Ukraine Association Agreement, demonstrating Ukraine’s commitment to closer integration with the European Union. The European Parliament gave its consent to the Agreement in parallel. The Rada also voted in favour of Ukraine submitting an application for EU membership.</p><p>On 25 September, President Poroshenko announced that Ukraine would submit a bid for membership of the EU in 2020.</p><p>We have consistently made clear our position that any European country that meets the criteria should be able to apply for EU membership; this includes Ukraine, if that is what the people of Ukraine want. Countries must meet all the rigorous conditions of membership in full before joining the EU. No bilateral representations on this issue have been received.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-10-15T12:39:53.4047584Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92213/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92213/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Ukraine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has received from the government of Ukraine on membership of the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","209673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92214","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The UK will fully engage in the Universal Periodic Review (UPR) of Iran’s human rights record, which is due to be considered by the Human Rights Council on 31 October 2014. As at the last UPR, the UK will make a statement and table recommendations on how Iran could improve its approach to human rights. This will include minority religious rights - the UK has repeatedly expressed concern at the persecution of the Baha’i community in Iran, and we will continue to encourage Iran to ensure all its citizens are able to exercise their right to freedom of religion, free from persecution and harassment.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-16T14:09:17.0442951Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92214/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92214/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if his Department will make recommendations to the UN Universal Periodic Review of the human rights record of Iran to encourage that state to cease its policies of persecution of members of the Bahá’í community; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","209697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92215","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>My Rt Hon Friend The Prime Minister, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) and the Secretary of State for Defence, my Rt Hon Friend the Member for Sevenoaks (Mr Fallon), discussed defence, deterrence and reassurance to Allies in relation a range of threats to the Alliance at the North Atlanitc Treaty Organisation (NATO) Summit in Wales on 4-5 September 2014.</p><p>As the Prime Minister set out in his statement to the House on 8 September, Official Report, column 653, the Wales Summit launched a NATO Readiness Action Plan which will enable NATO to respond faster to the new and emerging threats, including on NATO’s eastern border. To support this, the UK will continue to participate in assurance measures to support our Eastern Allies and contribute 3,500 personnel for exercises.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-10-15T12:38:12.1129565Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92215/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92215/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his NATO counterparts on defence of the eastern borders of the Alliance; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","209692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92216","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The UK will fully engage in the Universal Periodic Review (UPR) of Iran’s human rights record, which is due to be considered by the Human Rights Council on 31 October 2014. As at the last UPR, the UK will make a statement and table recommendations on how Iran could improve its approach to human rights. This will include minority religious rights - the UK has repeatedly expressed concern at the persecution of the Baha’i community in Iran, and we will continue to encourage Iran to ensure all its citizens are able to exercise their right to freedom of religion, free from persecution and harassment.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-16T14:09:49.3955443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92216/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92216/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what contribution the UK plans to make to the Universal Periodic Review of Iran's human rights record due to be considered by the UN Human Rights Council on 27 October 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","209698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92217","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>We regularly receive and make representations to the Belarusian government on human rights both bilaterally and through the EU, particularly on the release of political prisoners and the abolition of the Death Penalty. Most recently, in September our Ambassador in Belarus met with Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MFA) officials to discuss the Death Penalty. We have also recently engaged with the Belarusian MFA on the establishment of a National Human Rights Institution in Belarus.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-10-15T12:40:30.4686089Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92217/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92217/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Belarus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has received on human rights in Belarus; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","209668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92218","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>Uzbekistan remains a Country of Concern in our latest Annual Human Rights Report. We regularly raise our concerns directly with the Uzbek authorities, through our Embassy in Tashkent and at Ministerial level, most recently during Baroness Warsi’s visit to Tashkent as Senior Minister of State at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in meetings with Uzbek Ministerial counterparts in April this year. We also encourage further progress towards full implementation of Uzbekistan’s international human rights commitments, both bilaterally and with our international partners.</p><p>In addition to raising concerns, our Embassy in Tashkent funds projects that support good governance and human rights.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-15T13:02:44.8613369Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92218/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92218/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Uzbekistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Uzbekistan on reports of human rights abuses.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","209713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92219","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-10-27","<p>Israel is an important strategic partner of the UK and, as part of that relationship, the Ministry of Defence has an ongoing and wide ranging dialogue with the Israeli Defence Force and Israeli Ministry of Defence, including in the field of training. This engagement is in line with Her Majesty's Government policy of supporting the Middle East peace process by having a balanced relationship with the Israelis and the Palestinians. Engagement activity is spread throughout the Services so this information is not held in the requested format.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-10-27T16:43:06.6778074Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92219/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92219/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92219/answer/previousversion/22162","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-09-26","Israel Defence Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what military training the UK armed forces have (a) received from and (b) provided to the Israeli Defence Force in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","209806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92220","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>UN Security Council Resolution 2166 condemned the downing of Malaysian Airlines flight MH17 in the strongest possible terms and called for a full, thorough and independent international investigation. We continue to work closely with the Dutch Public Prosecutor’s Office (OM), which is leading the investigation.</p><p>As my Rt Hon Friend the Prime Minister has made clear, the weight of evidence is pointing in one direction: MH17 was shot down by a missile fired by pro-Russian separatists. We welcome the Dutch Safety Board’s preliminary report of 9 September which further supports this evidence and makes it clear that this was not the result of human or technical error.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-10-15T14:07:21.1287321Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92220/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92220/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Ukraine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress he has made in bringing to justice those responsible for the destruction of Malaysian Airlines flight MH17 on 17 July 2014.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","209807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92221","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>We have made it clear to the Chinese government that people who have escaped from North Korea are entitled to protection under the International Convention relating to the Status of Refugees (1951) and the Protocol Relating to the Status of Refugees (1967). We have also made clear we believe the Chinese government should allow people from the Democratic People's Republic of Korea safe passage to resettlement in third countries; and we encourage the Chinese government to work with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees to facilitate this. The then Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon Friend the Member for Richmond Yorks ( Mr Hague), raised human rights during his meeting with State Counsellor Yang Jiechi in February 2014, including the specific issue of non-refoulement of North Korean refugees. I also raised these issues with the Chinese Permanent Representative in Geneva in June 2014.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-10-16T14:06:16.4948546Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92221/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92221/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","North Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps he has taken to raise the issue of forced repatriations to North Korea with the Chinese government.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","209778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92222","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-29","<p>The UK continues to support the Nigerian authorities in trying to establish the location of the abducted schoolgirls. We provide surveillance assets, in the form of RAF Tornados, to assist in the search and expertise to assist in intelligence analysis. The resolve of Nigeria, the UK and international community to continue the search remains strong.</p><p>On 3 September I led the UK delegation to the ministerial meeting in Abuja on security in Nigeria, attended by Nigeria’s neighbours and international partners. I emphasised the crucial importance of regional coordination to locating the girls taken from Chibok and to defeating Boko Haram.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-10-29T14:51:14.4440106Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92222/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92222/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Arctic Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many officials there were in the UK delegation to the 2013 Arctic Council Ministerial meeting in Kiruna, Sweden; and what the (a) title of position and (b) grade was of each such official.","false","Biography information for Angus Robertson","Moray","Angus Robertson","209769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92223","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-14","<p>A range of officials from across Government departments input into the UK’s Arctic policy, reflecting the breadth of the UK’s policy interests in the Arctic as set out in the Government’s Arctic Policy Framework. Within the FCO, no one works exclusively on Arctic issues but a number of officials from across the office work collaboratively to develop the UK’s Arctic policy. The policy is coordinated by the Polar Regions Department, headed by a senior SMS1 official, and which chairs the cross-Government network. There is considerable input from posts in the eight Arctic States and the Arctic Council observer states, and from relevant policy officials and legal advisors in London on issues such as climate change, energy, international law and maritime policy.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-10-14T13:21:07.9936457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92223/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92223/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Arctic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many officials in his Department work exclusively on Arctic issues; and what the (a) title of position and (b) grade is of each such official.","false","Biography information for Angus Robertson","Moray","Angus Robertson","209768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92224","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-14","<p>The Government’s aim for the Arctic is to work towards a region that is safe and secure; well governed in conjunction with indigenous peoples and in line with international law; where policies are developed on the basis of sound science with full regard to the environment; and where only responsible development takes place. The UK supports the Canadian priorities for its Chairmanship of the Arctic Council, particularly around strengthening the Arctic Council; safe Arctic shipping; and responsible resource development, all of which are in line with the Government’s full Arctic policy as outlined in its Arctic Policy Framework: Adapting To Change, published in October 2013.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-10-14T13:12:59.1924686Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92224/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92224/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Arctic Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the goals of the UK are, as an Arctic Council observer state, for the Canadian chairmanship of the Arctic Council from 2013 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Angus Robertson","Moray","Angus Robertson","209760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92225","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>We have concerns about all restrictions placed on freedom of religion and belief in China, including those placed on Christians in Wenzhou, Zhejiang Province. We regularly raise our concerns with Chinese counterparts and did so most recently during the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue on 19-20 May 2014. We also raise our concerns publicly through our Annual Report on Human Rights and Democracy, last published on 10 April 2014 and updated on 30 June 2014.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-10-16T14:04:40.9926761Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92225/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92225/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions officials in his Department have had with the Chinese government on upholding the religious freedom of Christians in the Wenzhou, Zhejiang Province.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","209774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92226","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>The decision to move BBC Tamil to Delhi is a matter for the BBC World Service, which is as the hon. Member will know editorially, managerially and financially independent from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-10-15T11:33:30.6054962Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92226/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92226/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Tamils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will review the decision to move the BBC Tamil Service from London to Delhi; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Mr Gareth Thomas","209789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92227","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The new Civil Service Employee Policy Performance Management system applies to UK-based staff in the delegated grades (Band A (AA-AO) to Band D (G6/7). Senior Civil Servants (SCS) follow Cabinet Office guidance on performance management. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) adopted the new Performance Management System in April 2013. The Department operates a split appraisal cycle with Bands C (HEO/SEO) and D using the financial year and Bands A and B (AA/AO/EO) using the calendar year. Bands C and D used the new policy for appraisal year 2013/2014, with Band D appraisals being subject to performance validation. Bands A and B only started to use the new system from 1 January 2014 and will complete their cycle in December. The FCO uses the third box marking of “Partially Met” rather than “Must Improve”. We also have a guided distribution in place across the ratings as follows: Exceeded – 25% Met – 60% Partially Met – 15% The FCO takes seriously its obligations to collect diversity data as required by the Equality Act 2010. Information about the diversity and makeup of our staff is listed in the FCO's Diversity and Equality Report. We will complete an analysis of the appraisal and performance related pay (PRP) data for diversity purposes early in 2015 once all staff have completed one full year on the new system.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-16T14:03:54.7773034Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92227/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92227/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many officials in his Department of each (a) gender, (b) ethnicity and (c) age received the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System's (i) exceeded, (ii) met and (iii) must improve performance mark in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92228","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv discussed Israel’s cooperation with the UN Commission of Inquiry and meeting international standards of accountability as a whole with the Director of International Law at the Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs on 30 September. Officials have also lobbied Israeli Cabinet Ministers, the National Security Council and Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Members of the Knesset and Knesset officials, for Israel to address the international community’s concerns over the deaths of over 2000 Gazans.</p><p>We are pressing Israel to demonstrate accountability for its actions during the recent Gaza conflict. The Israel Defence Forces have launched a number of internal processes to investigate specific cases of engagement, and the Israeli State Comptroller has launched an investigation into the Government’s conduct. We will watch these closely. But there will also be international procedures which must examine the actions of both Hamas and Israel. Both sides should cooperate with the Commission of Inquiry set up by the UN Human Rights Council, which must itself be independent and balanced in its approach.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-15T13:13:41.9413143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92228/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92228/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with the government of Israel about potential breaches of international law by that country.","false","Biography information for Martin Horwood","Cheltenham","Martin Horwood","209581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92229","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>Iraqi forces, including the Peshmerga, are key parts of the fight against Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant (ISIL), as is the Syrian moderate opposition. Aircraft from Bahrain, Jordan, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates have been involved in airstrikes against the terrorist group in Syria. Other states in the region are also providing humanitarian, logistical and other support to international efforts to degrade and ultimately defeat ISIL.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-15T13:15:53.6991131Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92229/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92229/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what personnel and frontline fighter aircraft from Middle Eastern States will participate in the coalition against ISIL.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","209591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92230","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) met Bangladesh’s Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina in London in July. He noted the UK’s disappointment over Bangladesh’s parliamentary election in January 2014 with more than half of constituencies uncontested. They agreed on the importance of open society and a political system in which democratic political participation and media freedoms are respected. We have also raised concerns about human rights violations with the government of Bangladesh in the aftermath of elections and have continued to encourage dialogue between Bangladesh’s political parties to strengthen democratic accountability and to put an end to the damaging 5-cycle of one-sided elections, electoral violence and instability.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-10-15T11:29:39.7389177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92230/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92230/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Bangladesh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he had with the Bangladeshi Prime Minister on (a) international recognition of her recent election, (b) alleged human rights violations preceding that election and (c) the promotion of free, fair and inclusive elections in Bangladesh in future during her visit to the UK in January 2014.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull","Solihull","Lorely Burt","209602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92231","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-29","<p>I raised concerns about the proposed NGO bill with South Sudan Foreign Minister Dr Barnaba Benjamin during a meeting in New York on 25 September. I have since written to Dr Benjamin to reinforce those concerns and provide more detail. The British Embassy in Juba has also made a number of representations to the South Sudanese authorities on this issue over the past year. In September, I met a wide selection of British NGOs operating in South Sudan, to discuss, amongst other topics, their concern about the possible impact of the NGO bill.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-29T14:48:41.8817433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92231/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92231/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","South Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the authorities in South Sudan over the need for the NGO Bill in that country to ensure that citizens and civil society organisations can engage in humanitarian activity, enjoy freedom of association and use monitoring and accountability systems in accordance with the general assumptions of the New Deal.","false","Biography information for Mr William Bain","Glasgow North East","Mr William Bain","209554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92232","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-29","<p>The UK Government is committed to helping countries end the recruitment and use of children in conflict. <br> <br>During the United Nations General Assembly in New York, I hosted a Ministerial roundtable, chaired by the UN Special Representative of the Secretary General for Children and Armed Conflict, Ms Leila Zerrougui. The event brought together Afghanistan, Burma, Chad, Liberia, Sierra Leone, Somalia, South Sudan, Sudan, Yemen and African Union (AU) Commissioner for Peace and Security, Mr Smail Chergui.</p><p>The meeting looked at ways to end the recruitment and use of children in conflict by government forces, particularly through the implementation of UN Action Plans. It allowed countries that have successfully ended this practice to share lessons with those who are working towards this goal.</p><p>The roundtable built on an event during the End Sexual Violence in Conflict Summit in London in June, led by my Honourable friend Mark Simmonds MP, where Ministers from Sierra Leone, Democratic Republic of Congo and Somalia underlined their commitment to ending the recruitment and use of children in armed conflict.</p><p>The UK is also the majority funder of a Child Protection Adviser at the AU. This post is designed to ensure child protection policies are mainstreamed in AU peace enforcement operations on the continent.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-29T14:43:10.9112147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92232/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92232/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Armed Conflict: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking with African Union governments to end the recruitment of children into the national armed forces of countries where this practice takes place; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","209687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92233","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>The United Kingdom plans to contribute to an international mission observing the elections in Moldova. The mission is being led by the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe's (OSCE’s) Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights (OHDIR). We expect other EU Member States to do likewise.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-10-15T14:03:41.4510316Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92233/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92233/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Moldova","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking with his counterparts in the EU to ensure that the upcoming parliamentary elections in Moldova are free and fair; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","209669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92234","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The new Civil Service Employee Policy Performance Management system applies to UK-based staff in the delegated grades (Band A (AA-AO) to Band D (G6/7). Senior Civil Servants (SCS) follow Cabinet Office guidance on performance management.<br>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) adopted the new Performance Management System in April 2013. The Department operates a split appraisal cycle with Bands C (HEO/SEO) and D using the financial year and Bands A and B (AA/AO/EO) using the calendar year. Bands C and D used the new policy for appraisal year 2013/2014, with Band D appraisals being subject to performance validation. Bands A and B only started to use the new system from 1 January 2014 and will complete their cycle in December. The FCO uses the third box marking of “Partially Met” rather than “Must Improve”. We also have a guided distribution in place across the ratings as follows:<br>Exceeded – 25%<br>Met – 60%<br>Partially Met – 15%<br>The FCO takes seriously its obligations to collect diversity data as required by the Equality Act 2010. Information about the diversity and makeup of our staff is listed in the FCO's Diversity and Equality Report. We will complete an analysis of the appraisal and performance related pay (PRP) data for diversity purposes early in 2015 once all staff have completed one full year on the new system.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-16T14:08:25.3842415Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92234/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92234/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many officials in his Department completed the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System in 2013-14; how many and what proportion of those officials received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark; and how many and what proportion (i) did and (ii) did not qualify for a bonus under that process.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92235","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The new Civil Service Employee Policy Performance Management system applies to UK-based staff in the delegated grades (Band A (AA-AO) to Band D (G6/7). Senior Civil Servants (SCS) follow Cabinet Office guidance on performance management. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) adopted the new Performance Management System in April 2013. The Department operates a split appraisal cycle with Bands C (HEO/SEO) and D using the financial year and Bands A and B (AA/AO/EO) using the calendar year. Bands C and D used the new policy for appraisal year 2013/2014, with Band D appraisals being subject to performance validation. Bands A and B only started to use the new system from 1 January 2014 and will complete their cycle in December. The FCO uses the third box marking of “Partially Met” rather than “Must Improve”. We also have a guided distribution in place across the ratings as follows: Exceeded – 25% Met – 60% Partially Met – 15% The FCO takes seriously its obligations to collect diversity data as required by the Equality Act 2010. Information about the diversity and makeup of our staff is listed in the FCO's Diversity and Equality Report. We will complete an analysis of the appraisal and performance related pay (PRP) data for diversity purposes early in 2015 once all staff have completed one full year on the new system.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-16T14:11:39.634632Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92235/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92235/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many officials in his Department who received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark under the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System (i) had a disability, (ii) worked full-time and (iii) worked part-time in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209629"
