"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92301","Scotland Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. All staff join on assignment from other Government bodies, principally the Scottish Government and Ministry of Justice, which remain their employers. Detailed information in relation to the classification of staff and their performance management is held by the employers.</p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-10-16T10:25:34.8420054Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92301/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92301/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many officials in his Department who received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark under the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System (i) had a disability, (ii) worked full-time and (iii) worked part-time in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92302","Scotland Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. All staff join on assignment from other Government bodies, principally the Scottish Government and Ministry of Justice, which remain their employers. All permanent civil servants are appraised and evaluated under the performance management arrangements of their parent Department. Detailed information in relation to performance management markings and satisfying bonus criteria is a matter for those employers.</p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-10-16T10:28:54.263437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92302/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92302/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many officials in his Department completed the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System in 2013-14; how many and what proportion of those officials received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark; and how many and what proportion (i) did and (ii) did not qualify for a bonus under that process.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92303","Scotland Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. All staff join on assignment from other Government bodies, principally the Scottish Government and Ministry of Justice, which remain the employers. Detailed information in relation to the classification of staff and their performance management is held by the employers.</p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-10-16T10:27:13.5852637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92303/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92303/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many officials in his Department of what (a) gender, (b) ethnicity and (c) age received the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System's (i) exceeded, (ii) met and (iii) must improve performance mark in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92304","Scotland Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The Scotland Office’s records date from its establishment in 1999. Appropriate measures will be taken to ensure that its records are assessed for long term preservation in accordance with the prevailing practice in other departments.</p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-10-16T10:23:42.1228386Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92304/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92304/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-09-26","Public Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what targets have been set for the release of his Department's material to the National Archives; what progress has been made in meeting those targets; and how many staff in his Department are engaged in reviewing records for that purpose.","false","Biography information for Lord Beith","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Sir Alan Beith","209616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92305","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-16","<p>The target for the release of the Department’s material to The National Archives is set in connection with the 10-year transition to the 20 Year Rule. This means that in each year up to 2023 we need to transfer at least two years’ worth of the material. As part of the process all material is reviewed to identify those records that hold enduring historical value and should therefore be transferred. The department does not have targets relating to the volume of material to be transferred.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This transition period started in 2013 with material from 1983 and 1984, and to date we have met our statutory responsibility. This progress has resulted in the transfer of 404 records to The National Archives in 2013/14, increased from 272 records in 2012/13. We have the resources in place to continue to achieve compliance with the 20 Year Rule.</p><p> </p><p>There are one and a half full-time equivalent staff engaged in reviewing records to determine, in agreement with The National Archives, what should be transferred to them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-16T13:34:09.8702137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92305/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92305/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","Public Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what targets have been set for the release of his Department's material to the National Archives; what progress has been made in meeting those targets; and how many staff in his Department are engaged in reviewing records for that purpose.","false","Biography information for Lord Beith","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Sir Alan Beith","209617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92306","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-15","<p>The Department for Transport appointed a joint team of Parliamentary Agents to provide support in relation to High Speed 2 (HS2) in June 2012. The joint team is made up of Winckworth Sherwood and Eversheds. The legal fees paid to Winckworth Sherwood are £2,153,020.13 and to Eversheds are £1,747,312.30. These fees are correct up to the end of August 2014. For this financial year the remaining budget is approximately £1.4m.</p><p> </p><p>The Parliamentary Agents have provided advice on the hybrid Bill process, the development and preparation of private elements of the hybrid Bill and associated documents (i.e. including the hybrid Bill Plans and Sections, Environmental Statement, Code of Construction Practice etc.), supporting the engagement with key stakeholders and helping to manage the hybrid Bill through Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-15T10:51:52.5777241Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92306/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92306/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","Winckworth Sherwood","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department has paid to Winckworth Sherwood to date in relation to High Speed 2; and what budget his Department has set for fees to that firm.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","209595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92307","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-15","<p>The High Speed 2 (HS2) Phase One Information Papers, which are available on the HS2 Ltd website (www.hs2.org.uk), have been produced in-house by HS2 Ltd and the Department for Transport (DfT). The process for preparing these information papers includes the review and clearance of the papers by (i) HS2 Ltd and DfT colleagues; and (ii) members of the team of Parliamentary Agents and Legal Counsel appointed by DfT to support the passage of HS2 Phase One hybrid Bill.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","209750","2014-10-15T09:49:55.5621197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92307/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92307/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which contractor his Department used to write the High Speed 2 Information Papers; and what fee his Department paid for that work.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","209596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92308","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-14","<p>The attached table provides the information requested. The figures for ethnicity are based on employees who have declared their ethnicity and exclude those of unknown ethnicity.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The information in the response excludes the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency and Vehicle Certification Agency which do not have comparable performance management systems.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-14T14:41:07.616492Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92308/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92308/answer","141014 - UIN 209291 - Performance management marks 2013-14.xls","141014 - UIN 209291 - Performance management marks 2013-14.xls","209491_ table performance management marks 2013-14","209491_ table performance management marks 2013-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92308/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many officials in his Department of what (a) gender, (b) ethnicity and (c) age received the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System's (i) exceeded, (ii) met and (iii) must improve performance mark in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92309","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-17","<p>The current estimated cost of Phase 1 of High Speed 2 (London to West Midlands) is £15.65 billion. A contingency provision of £5.75 billion has been set at P95 level. Based on these prices the cost per single track kilometre is £47.56 million for Phase 1, including £80, 000 per kilometre for noise barriers. These figures are in 2011 prices and at the P95 level, meaning that at this early stage there is a 95 percent confidence level that the project can be delivered for this cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","209701","2014-10-17T12:08:32.1510618Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92309/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92309/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the Government's latest projected cost is for the London to Birmingham stretch of High Speed 2, with contingency identified separately.","false","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman","209686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92310","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-14","<p>The table below provides the data requested</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td>exceeded</td><td>met</td><td>must improve</td><td>Total</td></tr><tr><td>number of staff</td><td>1,402</td><td>7,106</td><td>755</td><td>9,263</td></tr><tr><td>proportion of staff</td><td>15%</td><td>77%</td><td>8%</td><td>100%</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>9,263 employees in the Department completed the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System in 2013/14. This does not include 4688 employees in the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency and 158 employees in the Vehicle Certification Agency as these Agencies do not have a comparable performance management system.</p><p> </p><p>(i) 1,402 employees (15%) qualified for a bonus and</p><p>(ii) 7,861 employees (85%) did not qualify for a bonus under that process.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-14T15:37:27.4552108Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92310/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92310/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many officials in his Department completed the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System in 2013-14; how many and what proportion of those officials received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark; and how many and what proportion (i) did and (ii) did not qualify for a bonus under that process.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92311","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-14","<p>The table below provides the information requested. The figures for disability are based on employees who have declared their disability status.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td><strong>exceeded </strong></td><td><strong>met </strong></td><td><strong>must improve </strong></td><td><strong>Total </strong></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><strong>All staff </strong></td><td>1,402</td><td>7,106</td><td>755</td><td>9,263</td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><strong>Disability status </strong></td><td><strong>Non-disabled</strong></td><td>1,108</td><td>5,466</td><td>504</td><td>7,078</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Disabled</strong></td><td>69</td><td>494</td><td>70</td><td>633</td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><strong>Working pattern </strong></td><td><strong>Full-time </strong></td><td>1,288</td><td>6,114</td><td>638</td><td>8,040</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Part-time </strong></td><td>114</td><td>992</td><td>117</td><td>1,223</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The information provided in the response excludes the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency and Vehicle Certification Agency which do not have comparable performance management systems.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-14T15:12:43.2701544Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92311/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92311/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many officials in his Department who received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark under the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System (i) had a disability, (ii) worked full-time and (iii) worked part-time in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92312","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-15","<p>The High Speed 2 (HS2) Phase One Information Papers, which are available on the HS2 Ltd website (www.hs2.org.uk), have been produced in-house by HS2 Ltd and the Department for Transport (DfT). The process for preparing these information papers includes the review and clearance of the papers by (i) HS2 Ltd and DfT colleagues; and (ii) members of the team of Parliamentary Agents and Legal Counsel appointed by DfT to support the passage of HS2 Phase One hybrid Bill.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","209596","2014-10-15T09:49:55.6746007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92312/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92312/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what process of peer review and challenge (a) his Department and (b) HS2 Ltd undertook in respect of the production of the High Speed 2 Information Papers.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","209750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92313","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-17","<p>The current estimated cost of Phase 1 of High Speed 2 (London to West Midlands) is £15.65 billion. A contingency provision of £5.75 billion has been set at P95 level. Based on these prices the cost per single track kilometre is £47.56 million for Phase 1, including £80, 000 per kilometre for noise barriers. These figures are in 2011 prices and at the P95 level, meaning that at this early stage there is a 95 percent confidence level that the project can be delivered for this cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","209686","2014-10-17T12:08:32.4635616Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92313/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92313/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the projected cost per kilometre is of the London to Birmingham stretch of High Speed 2; and what the projected cost per kilometre is of noise barriers on that stretch.","false","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman","209701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92314","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-17","<p>The figure of 350MW for peak power demand for the Phase 1 network at the maximum planned capacity (18 trains per hour in each direction) is still the current estimate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The maximum operating speed associated with this figure is 360 kph.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-17T11:49:14.0076344Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92314/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92314/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-26","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 5 September 2013 to Question 167787, whether the figure of 350Mw given in that Answer is still accurate; and what the maximum operating speed associated with this figure is.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","209699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92315","Wales Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>The breakdown requested for Wales Office staff’s performance marks is shown below. As some of the data relates to fewer than five staff, breaking the numbers down would risk the identification of individuals and so only percentages are provided. Data for part-time staff is withheld as it would lead to direct identification<strong>.</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong> (a) </strong><strong>Exceeded </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> (b) </strong><strong>Met </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> (c) </strong><strong>Must improve </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> Not declared</strong></p><p><strong> or not stated</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(i) Percentage of staff who declared themselves disabled</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>46%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(ii) Worked Full-time</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td><td><p>82%</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2014-10-16T10:43:37.1606408Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92315/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92315/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many officials in his Department who received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark under the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System (i) had a disability, (ii) worked full-time and (iii) worked part-time in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92316","Wales Office","false","2014-10-15","<p>All staff in the Wales Office including agency staff who had been in post for longer than a month participated in the completion of the Civil Service Employment Performance System in 2013-14. Of these (a) 14% received exceeded (b) 78% received met and (c) 8% received must improve performance marks; (i) 5% did and (ii) 95% did not qualify for a bonus.</p><p>As some of the data relates to fewer than five staff, breaking the numbers down would risk the identification of individuals and so only percentages are provided.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2014-10-15T15:15:13.2228727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92316/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92316/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2014-09-26","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many officials in his Department completed the Civil Service Employment Policy Performance Management System in 2013-14; how many and what proportion of those officials received the (a) exceeded, (b) met and (c) must improve performance mark; and how many and what proportion (i) did and (ii) did not qualify for a bonus under that process.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","209662"
