ty conservation through agri-environment schemes, plant health and pesticide safety.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-13T16:08:50.1798249Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91724/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91724/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-12","Agriculture: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much her Department spent on agricultural research in each year from 1997-98 to 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","209241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91725","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-20","<p>The Welfare of Greyhound Regulations 2010 are set for review five years after they were made in April 2010. Defra is beginning the review now by gathering evidence on the operation of the regulations with a view to completing the review after the General Election in May 2015.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-20T16:05:44.0766835Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91725/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91725/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-12","Greyhound Racing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department's review of the Welfare of Racing Greyhounds Regulation planned for 2015 will take place before the General Election.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","209265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91726","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-13","<p>Surveillance and monitoring is carried out across the UK to provide intelligence on the rate of spread for Chalara and to help determine the extent of the disease. This work will continue on new infected sites and, in consultation with interested parties, the Government will consider what future surveillance work is needed.</p><p>Epidemiological modelling on the basis of current evidence suggests that the pathogen is likely to continue to spread in Great Britain, although there is likely to be noticeable regional variation, with areas in the south east, east and south west most affected. These predictions will need to be updated as additional information from ongoing research becomes available. The distribution of confirmed findings is published weekly by the Forestry Commission on its website and shows the precise coverage so far. I attach the latest map here but further updates can be found by using the following link.</p><p><a href="http://www.forestry.gov.uk/chalara#Distribution" target="_blank">http://www.forestry.gov.uk/chalara#Distribution</a></p><p>The impact of Chalara infection depends on tree age, provenance or genotype, location, weather and microclimate conditions, and presence of honey fungus (<em>Armillaria)</em> or opportunistic secondary pathogens. Trees in forests are likely to be more affected because of the greater prevalence of honey fungus and favourable microclimates for spore production and infection. Trees cannot recover from infection, but larger trees can survive infection for a considerable time and some might not die.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-13T16:08:57.0079026Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91726/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91726/answer","209260 - chalara fraxinea outbreaks map.pdf","209260 - chalara fraxinea outbreaks map.pdf","Chalera Fraxinia Outbreaks Map","Chalera Fraxinia Outbreaks Map","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91726/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-12","Ash Dieback Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the (a) geographical spread and (b) effect of ash dieback disease.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","209260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91727","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-13","<p>Defra and the Forestry Commission do not record or make estimates of numbers of individual tree deaths. Chalara has infected many species of ash worldwide, with differing levels of intensity. Trees cannot recover once infected, although larger ash trees can survive infection for a considerable period of time.</p><p>Epidemiological modelling on the basis of current evidence suggests that the pathogen is likely to continue to spread in Great Britain, although there is likely to be noticeable regional variation, with areas in the south east, east and south west most affected. These predictions will need to be updated as additional information from ongoing research becomes available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-13T15:49:46.7922574Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91727/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91727/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-12","Ash Dieback Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of how many and what proportion of ash trees are likely to die from ash dieback disease.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","209261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91728","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-13","<p>Defra and the Government Office for Science will be publishing Sir Mark Walport’s study entitled <em>‘</em><em>Animal &amp; Plant Health in the UK: An Assessment of Future Science Capability</em>’ in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-13T16:02:46.2085482Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91728/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91728/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-12","Animals and Plants: Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish Sir Mark Walport's study on the UK's future needs for capability in animal and plant health.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","209249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91729","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-16","<p>This is subject to a commercial confidentiality restriction and all companies have signed a confidentiality agreement. Therefore, we are not in the position to disclose publicly the names of the companies until after the procurement is completed. We are in the middle of a public procurement under EU regulations.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-16T16:45:04.1570925Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91729/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91729/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-12","Food and Environment Research Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which companies responded to the Food and Environment Research Agency market sounding exercise.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","209250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91730","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-13","<p>Research by Natural England and the Joint Nature Conservation Committee has identified that 1,058 species have all or part of their lifecycle associated with ash woodlands in the UK, for example as a habitat, food source or hunting ground. Of these only 45 are exclusively recorded on ash, with a further 62 highly associated but also recorded on other species. No single tree species will be able to fill the niche provided by ash trees in terms of both its ecosystem characteristics and biodiversity contribution. The most appropriate strategy for managing the biodiversity impacts of ash dieback will vary from site to site.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-13T15:55:47.6675203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91730/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91730/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-12","Ash Dieback Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the ecological effect of ash dieback disease on the countryside.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","209246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91731","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-13","<p>Research is being undertaken to produce genetic maps of the pathogen and of ash trees to allow identification and breeding of resistant or tolerant ash trees and, where appropriate, improve detection techniques.</p><p>Ash saplings have been planted in areas with a high risk of infection to identify trees with resistance or tolerance to the disease. Ash seeds have been collected from a number of locations across the UK to be used in future screening and breeding programmes.</p><p>Standardised techniques for producing infection in the laboratory are being developed. This will allow disease development to be assessed under controlled conditions. This will be essential for identifying genetic markers for host resistance for use in breeding programmes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-13T15:52:55.6327441Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91731/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91731/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-09-12","Ash Dieback Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress her Department has made in identifying ash trees with resistance to ash dieback disease; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","209247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91732","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>The Preventing Sexual Violence Initiative (PSVI) is focused on ending impunity for crimes of sexual violence committed in conflict and the provision of greater support to the survivors of these crimes. Where caste based sexual violence and so-called punishment rape are used in conflict they fall within the overarching objectives of the Initiative.</p><p>The UK’s National Action Plan (NAP) on implementing UN Security Council Resolution 1325 reaffirms and strengthens the Government’s ambition to pursue visible change for women and girls affected by conflict. The 2014-2017 NAP promotes the participation of women, from all backgrounds, in decision-making processes related to the prevention, management and resolution of conflicts.</p><p>PSVI and the NAP are complemented by wider government activity on tackling violence against women and girls, underpinned by the cross-government action plan, ‘A Call to End Violence against Women and Girls’, which sets out the Government’s programme of domestic and international work in this area. This includes working though our network of embassies overseas and with non-governmental organisations to address the full range of violations of women’s rights, including sexual and other forms of violence committed against them</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-10-13T14:43:58.3256055Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91732/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91732/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-12","UN Resolutions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure women from caste communities are taken into account in the Preventing Sexual Violence Initiative and the UN Security Council Resolution 1325 National Action Plan.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","209217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91733","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-14","<p>We have no plans to respond in writing to the report by the UN Special Rapporteur on Counter-Terrorism dated 28 February 2014. However, the United Kingdom was represented at the UN Human Rights Council expert meeting on 22 September, where we once again set out our position on the legality of Remotely Piloted Air Systems.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-14T13:07:14.0198549Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91733/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91733/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-12","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 17 March 2014 to Question 191665, if his Department will respond in writing to the final report of the UN Special Rapporteur on Counter-Terrorism dated 28 February 2014 by the Human Rights Council expert meeting on 22 September 2014 concerning the use of armed drones.","false","Biography information for John Hemming","Birmingham, Yardley","John Hemming","209216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91734","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-14","<p>I have not had any formal discussions with ministerial colleagues about the proposal for a no-take Marine Protected Area (MPA) within Pitcairn’s Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) since being appointed Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office on 11 August 2014. Senior officials are currently considering these proposals and will provide advice to Ministers in due course.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-10-14T13:20:06.0103746Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91734/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91734/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-12","Pitcairn Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues as part of the process of approval of marine protection for the Pitcairn Islands; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Joan Walley","Stoke-on-Trent North","Joan Walley","209219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91735","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>NATO invited participants to the UK hosted NATO Summit following their own strict protocol arrangements for delegation composition and size.</p><p>As host, the UK was able to influence directly the events around the NATO programme. As confirmation of our commitment to the Women, Peace and Security agenda, my Rt. Hon. Friend the Prime Minister’s Special Representative for Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict, my Rt. Hon. Friend the Member for Richmond (Yorks) (Mr Hague), hosted the first meeting of its kind at a NATO Summit with the NATO Secretary General’s Special Representative on Women, Peace and Security and the Foreign Ministers of Croatia and Denmark. The meeting launched NATO’s new Policy and Action Plan on Women, Peace and Security and announced the permanency of the Special Representative’s position who will lead NATO’s efforts to ensure that women’s participation in conflict resolution is seen and taken forward as an integral part of the peace and security agenda. The meeting also discussed how this work contributes to preventing conflict-related sexual and gender-based violence.</p><p>Furthermore, we enabled the Non-Government Organisation, the Atlantic Council to hold a ‘Future Leaders’ event in the margins of the NATO Summit. That was an opportunity for young professionals from all NATO member states and beyond to discuss implementation of UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 1325. The Deputy Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Sheffield, Hallam (Mr Clegg), was the lead UK speaker at the Future Leaders’ event. He took the opportunity to underline the importance of the UK’s National Action Plan for implementation of UNSCR 1325. The NATO Secretary General’s Special Representative on Women Peace and Security also spoke at the Future Leaders event.</p><p>We ensured the Summit Communiqué highlighted the importance of ensuring women's full and active participation in the prevention, management, and resolution of conflicts, as well as in post-conflict efforts and cooperation.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-10-13T13:30:27.0620894Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91735/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91735/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-12","Conflict Resolution: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how his Department implemented at the Newport NATO Summit its responsibility under the UK National Action Plan on UNSCR 1325 to ensure that women are fully and meaningfully represented at any international peacebuilding event or summit hosted by the UK.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","209243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91736","HM Treasury","false","2014-10-13","<p>The Government is actively engaged in ongoing discussions in a number of international fora, to reform the framework for sovereign debt restructurings. As outlined in the joint-EU Explanation of Vote on this Resolution, the Government was not in a position to support this UN resolution given concerns over the lack of time afforded to members to discuss the complex issues it raised.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","209075","2014-10-13T15:10:57.1815348Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91736/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91736/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-09-12","Public Sector Debt: UN Resolutions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, why the UK voted against United Nations General Assembly Resolution A/68/L.57/Rev.1 Towards the establishment of a multilateral legal framework for sovereign debt restructuring processes.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","209159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91737","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2014-10-13T08:34:12.046267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91737/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91737/answer","PQ 209166.pdf","PQ 209166.pdf","ONS Letter to Member - Alcohol Related Deaths","ONS Letter to Member - Alcohol Related Deaths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91737/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-09-12","Alcoholic Drinks: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many alcohol related deaths there were in (a) Preston and (b) other local authority areas in Lancashire, Cumbria, Greater Manchester and Cheshire in (i) 2011, (ii) 2012 and (iii) 2013.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","209166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91738","Department of Health","false","2014-10-17","<p>The information is not available in the format requested. The following table shows the number of finished admission episodes with a primary diagnosis of malnutrition by clinical commissioning group (CCG) of treatment for the Preston and Cumbria areas, and by NHS England Area Team of treatment for the Lancashire, Greater Manchester, and Cheshire areas, for the financial years 2010-11, 2011-12, and 2012-13.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NHS Greater Preston CCG</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NHS Cumbria CCG</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cheshire, Warrington and Wirral Area Team</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater Manchester Area Team</p></td><td><p>38</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>63</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lancashire Area Team ‡</p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>‡ Lancashire Area Team includes Preston CCG within its geographical boundary.</p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Hospital Episode Statistics (HES), Health and Social Care Information Centre</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p> </p><ol start="1" type="1"><li>To protect patient confidentiality, figures between 1 and 5 have been replaced with “*” (an asterisk).</li><li>A finished admission episode (FAE) is the first period of inpatient care under one consultant within one healthcare provider. FAEs are counted against the year in which the admission episode finishes. Admissions do not represent the number of inpatients, as a person may have more than one admission within the year.</li><li>ICD-10 codes used to identify admissions due to malnutrition:</li></ol><p> </p><p>E40.X - Kwashiorkor</p><p> </p><p>E41.X - Nutritional marasmus</p><p> </p><p>E42.X - Marasmic kwashiorkor</p><p> </p><p>E43.X - Unspecified severe protein-energy malnutrition</p><p> </p><p>E44.0 - Moderate protein-energy malnutrition</p><p> </p><p>E44.1 - Mild protein-energy malnutrition</p><p> </p><p>E45.X - Retarded development following protein-energy malnutrition</p><p> </p><p>E46.X - Unspecified protein-energy malnutrition</p><p> </p><p>O25.X - Malnutrition in pregnancy</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-10-17T13:19:27.7483552Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91738/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91738/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-12","Malnutrition: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospital admissions there were for malnutrition in (a) Preston and (b) other local authority areas in Lancashire, Cumbria, Greater Manchester and Cheshire in (i) 2010, (ii) 2011, (iii) 2012 and (iv) 2013.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","209167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91739","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2014-10-13T08:38:03.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91739/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91739/answer","PQ 209168.pdf","PQ 209168.pdf","ONS Letter to Member - Children born underweight","ONS Letter to Member - Children born underweight","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91739/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-09-12","Low Birthweight Babies: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many children were born underweight in (a) Preston and (b) other local authority areas in Lancashire, Cumbria, Greater Manchester and Cheshire in (i) 2010, (ii) 2011, (iii) 2012 and (iv) 2013.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","209168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91740","Department of Health","false","2014-10-13","<p>Incidents reported to the National Reporting and Learning System (NRLS) do not include information about which clinical commissioning group (CCG) commissioned the care where the incident occurred. Only the reporting organisation is included. As such, the information requested linking the incidents to CCGs is not collected or held centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The NRLS receives reports coded by level of harm. Of the 617 incidents reported between 20 March 2014 and 21 July 2014, 506 resulted in no harm, 94 ‘low’ harm, and 17 resulted in ‘moderate’ harm.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The NRLS does not record excess days in hospital or additional costs to the National Health Service arising from reported incidents.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-10-13T13:52:42.2579924Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91740/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91740/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-12","Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 3 September 2014, to Question 206600, in which clinical commissioning group each of the 617 incidents between 20 March 2014 and 21 July 2014 took place; and what assessment he has made of (a) patient harm, (b) excess days in hospital and (c) additional costs to the NHS resulting from those incidents.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","209177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91741","Department of Health","false","2014-10-17","<p>There have been no meetings between the Department or its Ministers and the North West Ambulance Service NHS Trust since June 2010.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-17T13:55:37.3783436Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91741/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91741/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-12","Ambulance Services: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what meetings his Department has had with North West Ambulance service since June 2010; and in how many such meetings (a) lack of ambulance cover, (b) ambulance waiting times and (c) use of Chloe Care and other private operators were discussed.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","209165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91742","Department of Health","false","2014-10-22","<p>As the commercial negotiations with Novartis are confidential and this includes any assessments made to inform the negotiations, it is not possible to provide the information requested.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-22T16:13:44.5579921Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91742/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91742/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-12","Meningitis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the sale of the Bexsero form of meningococcal group B vaccine to GlaxoSmithKline on (a) his Department's negotiations with Novartis on a price for the vaccine and (b) the roll out of that vaccine.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","209253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91743","Department of Health","false","2014-10-17","<p>The information requested is set out in the following table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of research licences granted</p></td><td><p>Number of research licences refused</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>158</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-17T13:34:33.6795946Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91743/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91743/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-12","Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many research licences were (a) granted and (b) refused by the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","209231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91744","Department of Health","false","2014-10-17","<p>This information is not collected by the Department. The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority does not collect this information as it is not part of its statutory duties.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that animal-human admixed embryos are not permitted for direct use in treatment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-17T13:37:17.2893509Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91744/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91744/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-09-12","Human-Animal Hybrid Embryos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many treatments have resulted from research conducted upon animal-human admixed embryos in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","209229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91745","Home Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>I refer to the Written Ministerial Statement of 12 December 2013, Official Report, column 58WS, in which I announced that the Coalition Government would conduct a review into new psychoactive substances led by a panel of experts.<br><br>I have now considered the expert panel’s report on the new psychoactive substances review including consideration of possible responses to the existence of &quot;head shops&quot;. The Government will respond to the expert panel’s report and its recommendations shortly.<br><br>The Coalition Government has already banned hundreds of new psychoactive substances. We have published guidance to support local authorities and continue to work closely with law enforcement to tackle this reckless trade.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-10-16T13:36:40.3375386Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91745/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91745/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-09-12","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to bring forward legislative proposals to introduce new powers to close shops selling legal highs.","false","Biography information for Mr Jeremy Browne","Taunton Deane","Mr Jeremy Browne","209220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91746","Home Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>The numbers of business visitor visas issued to (a) Indian and (b) Chinese nationals in each of the last three years for which figures are available are set out in the following table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Calendar Year</p><p> </p></td><td><p>(a) India</p></td><td><p>(b) China</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p><p> </p></td><td><p>69,786</p></td><td><p>69,457</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p><p> </p></td><td><p>67,221</p></td><td><p>71,863</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p><p> </p></td><td><p>71,881</p></td><td><p>68,972</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Note: UK destination only. Visit-Business endorsement only.</em></p><p> </p><p><em>Please note that all the figures given are sourced from management information which is not quality assured under National Statistics protocols and is subject to change due to internal data quality checking. Figures provided from this source do not constitute part of National Statistics and should be treated as provisional.</em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK is open for business to the brightest and best migrants and continues to welcome top global talent. Recent improvements to our visa services have reduced red tape and increased flexibility for businesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-10-13T11:05:27.3332669Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91746/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91746/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-09-12","Entry Clearances: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many business visitor visas were granted to (a) Indian and (b) Chinese nationals in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","209242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91747","Home Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>353,436 business visitor visas were issued in 2013. This includes all nationalities to UK destinations only. <br><br>Please note that this is sourced from management information which is not quality assured under National Statistics protocols and is subject to change due to internal data quality checking.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-10-13T11:06:04.6277097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91747/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91747/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-09-12","Entry Clearances: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many business visitor visas were granted in 2013.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","209240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91748","Home Office","false","2014-10-16","<p>I refer to the Written Ministerial Statement of 12 December 2013, Official Report, column 58WS, in which I announced that the Coalition Government would conduct a review into new psychoactive substances led by a panel of experts. I have now considered the expert panel’s report on the review. The Government will respond to the expert panel’s report and its recommendations shortly.<br><br>The Coalition Government has already banned over three hundred and fifty new psychoactive substances. We work closely with law enforcement to tackle this reckless trade.<br><br>&quot;Gocaine&quot; is a brand name used for compounds advertised as new psychoactive substances. &quot;Gocaine&quot; samples analysed through the Home Office Forensic Early Warning System (FEWS) suggest the brand is usually associated with a mixture of compounds, including methiopropamine (MPA) and methylenedioxy-2-aminiondane (MDAI). <br><br>Neither of these substances is currently controlled under the Misuse of Drugs Act 1971. However, we continue to update our drug controls under that Act in response to the availability and harms of new psychoactive substances. Such controls are informed by independent expert advice through a system of regular reviews by the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs (ACMD) which monitors the situation in the UK, including MPA and MDAI.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-10-16T13:41:50.4480089Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91748/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91748/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-09-12","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has any plans to introduce legislative proposals to criminalise the legal high known as gocaine.","false","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","209170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91749","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-10-13","<p>Mr Speaker did not interview any internal or external candidates engaged in the selection process for the Clerk of the House and Chief Executive before their interviews with the selection panel.</p><p>Internal and external applicants selected for interview all took the opportunity for an informal meeting with Mr Speaker.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-10-13T12:22:45.0035063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91749/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91749/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-09-12","Clerk of the House","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, whether Mr Speaker interviewed any (a) internal and (b) external candidates engaged in the selection process for the Clerk of the House and Chief Executive, before their interviews with the selection panel for that post.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","209171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91750","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-10-13","<p>Following the interview panel a letter was sent to Ms Mills by Mr Speaker informing her that, in accordance with procedures, her name and approved biographical details had been sent to the Prime Minister so that he might present them to Her Majesty The Queen for approval.</p><p>The letter was not an offer of employment as the Clerk of the House is appointed by the Crown by letters patent, on the recommendation of the Speaker and the Prime Minister. House of Commons human resource staff did not provide advice on the content of this letter.</p><p> </p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-10-13T12:22:02.4038395Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91750/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91750/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-09-12","Clerk of the House","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, whether House of Commons human resource officers provided advice on the content of the final offer letter sent to Ms Mills for the post of Clerk of the House and Chief Executive.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","209155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91751","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-10-13","<p>No external candidates were offered a meeting with the Speaker before they made their application.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-10-13T12:24:08.3354795Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91751/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91751/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-09-12","Clerk of the House","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, in respect of the selection process for the Clerk of the House and Chief Executive, whether external candidates for the post of Clerk of the House and Chief Executive were offered an informal meeting with the Speaker before they made their application.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","209263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91752","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-10-13","<p>Yes.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-10-13T12:24:36.5743248Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91752/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91752/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-09-12","Clerk of the House","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, whether selection panel members were aware that Mr Speaker was writing to the Prime Minister recommending that Carol Mills be appointed Clerk of the House and Chief Executive before or at the time that Mr Speaker did so.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","209264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91753","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-10-13","<p>It is not the Commission’s practice to disclose details of the interview process; however, one panel member declared knowledge of two external candidates during the panel’s discussions.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-10-13T12:23:15.5164297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91753/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91753/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-09-12","Clerk of the House","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, pursuant to the Answer of 10 September 2014 to Question 207921, which panel members chose to declare their prior knowledge of external candidates; and to which external candidates such declarations related.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","209224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91754","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-10-13","<p>It is not the Commission’s practice to disclose confidential personal information of this nature.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-10-13T12:23:42.0152061Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91754/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91754/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-09-12","Clerk of the House","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, what communication the House has received from Mr David Natzler regarding the questionnaire stage of Employment Tribunal proceedings by Mr Natzler in relation to the appointment of the Clerk of the House and Chief Executive.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","209225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91755","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-16","<p>The UK pledged at the conference to contribute £20 million, however, we made it clear that reconstruction in Gaza will require a durable ceasefire, an agreed approach on security, predictable and sustained access for people and goods in and out of Gaza, and good governance arrangements.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-10-16T16:14:40.4936422Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91755/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91755/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-09-12","Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions her Department has had with the co-hosts of the Gaza donor conference.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","209153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91756","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-16","<p>The UK pledged at the conference to contribute £20 million. We are clear, however, that reconstruction in Gaza will require a durable ceasefire, an agreed approach on security, predictable and sustained access for people and goods in and out of Gaza, and good governance arrangements.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-10-16T16:11:09.3017192Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91756/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91756/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-09-12","Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what aid commitments her Department intends to make at the Gaza donor conference.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","209154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91757","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-16","<p>DFID’s provision of humanitarian aid to Gaza is based on need, not on progress in the Middle East Peace Process. The UK has been one of the biggest donors to the Gaza crisis, providing more than £17 million of emergency assistance, and has pledged to provide a further £20million towards the cost of reconstruction.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-10-16T16:15:07.8797078Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91757/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91757/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-09-12","Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department's provision of humanitarian aid to Gaza is contingent on progress in the peace process between Israelis and the Palestinians.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","209180"
